title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
Hi guys this time I have a 820-00163 board with no water damage or corrosion. I checked:
PPBUS_G3H 8.6v
PP3V42_G3H. 3.43v
PP5V_S5 5v
PP3V3_S5. 3.3v
PP5V_S4RS3. 0v 
PLT_RESET_L 0v 
PM_PCH_SYS_PWROK 0v
SMC_ONOFF_L 3,43v
PM_PWRBTN_L 3,42v
PM_SLP_S4_L 0v
PM_SLP_S3_L 0v

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
Please confirm the exact model board.

Do you get 3V3_SUS and PM_BATLOW_L?

title: 820-00165 No Power
message: Trigger SMC_ONOFF_L and check for drop pulse at PM_PWRBTN_L, at same time.

title: 820-00165 No Power
message: PM_PWRBTN_L 3.42 to constant 0,352V when SMC_ONOFF_L is triggered

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
Check for pulse at PM_SLP_S4_L at same time.
Trigger SMC_ONOFF_L, to allow a higher pulse, if possible.

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
PM_SLP_S4_L  3,3V drops to 0 in a second when SMC_ONOFF_L is triggered

It only pulsates times

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
Do you mean PM_SLP_S4_L is steady high and drops to 0V when trigger SMC_ONOFF_L???

What this means then?
"PM_SLP_S4_L 0v"

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
I'm sorry my mistake
PM_SLP_S4_L pulse from 0v to 3.4v  all the time, does not matter trigger SMC_ONOFF_L

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
When you connect charger, PM_SLP_S4_L pulses in cycle, or just two times?
If pulses at least once, all S3 voltages should pulse at same time.
Also check for pulse at PM_SLP_S3_L and S0 voltages.
Any pulse at ALL_SYS_PWRGD?

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
Pulses all the time
PM_SLP_S3_L pulse  0v to 3.4v
PM_SLP_S0_L constant voltage 3.33v
ALL_SYS_PWRGD pulse  0v to 3.4v

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
PLT_RESET_L pulsing too?
If not, check for pulse at pins 5, 6 & 3 of U1950.

title: 820-00165 No Power
message: Check for pulse at CPU_VR_READY and CPU_VCCST_PWRGD.

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
CPU_VR_READY pulse 0v to 1v
CPU_VCCST_PWRGD pulse 0v to 1v

title: 820-00165 No Power
message:
Looks like PCH issue, as PLT_RESET_L dpesn't pulse at all.
You should check all SPI Bus Series Termination resistors and their traces.
Also try known good BIOS, just in case.
